OBJECTIVE

The objective of this task is to design, configure, and deploy an Intrusion Detection System (IDS) using Snort on Windows in order to monitor network traffic, detect suspicious activity, and analyze packet behavior in real time.

TOOLS & TECHNOLOGIES USED

• Snort 2.9.20 (Windows)
• Npcap
• Microsoft Windows 10
• Command Prompt
• GitHub

SYSTEM CONFIGURATION

Installation Steps

Installed Npcap for packet capturing.

Installed Snort 2.9.20 on Windows.

Created required directories:

C:\Snort\log
C:\Snort\rules

RULE CONFIGURATION

A custom rule file named local.rules was created and linked in snort.conf.
The network interface was identified using the following command:

snort -W

RUNNING SNORT IN IDS MODE

The following command was used to start Snort in IDS mode:

snort -i 4 -c C:\Snort\etc\snort.conf -A console -l C:\Snort\log

TESTING & MONITORING

After starting the IDS, live network traffic was captured and analyzed in real time.
The system inspected different types of packets including TCP, UDP, ICMP, IPv4, and IPv6.
Snort generated detailed runtime statistics such as:

• Packet processing performance
• Session tracking information
• Protocol distribution
• Memory usage statistics

Screenshots of configuration steps and live output were recorded as proof of successful implementation.

RESULTS

The Intrusion Detection System successfully:

• Captured live network traffic
• Analyzed packets in real time
• Generated detailed network statistics
• Operated continuously without errors

This confirms the successful deployment and functionality of the Snort IDS.

